                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d462">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/6875: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1925-12-24T18:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 24, 1925—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>347. Legation’s Number 544 of December 24, 5 p.m., including identic telegram.
                    Unless lives of American citizens are actually in danger, the Department would
                    disapprove of the use of force; and from statement in fifth paragraph of your
                    telegram it is assumed that the necessity to use force, which was apparent when
                    the identic telegram was drawn up, no longer exists.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
